        <section class="pipeline-section">
            <h3>Pipeline Architecture</h3>
            <div class="pipeline-steps">
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-number">1. Extract</div>
                    <strong>fetch_data.py</strong>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        Retrieves daily OHLCV market data from Yahoo Finance API. Handles MultiIndex DataFrames, 
                        normalizes column names, implements robust error handling for API failures.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-number">2. Load</div>
                    <strong>load_to_db.py</strong>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        Stores normalized data in SQLite with proper schema, composite primary keys, and indexing. 
                        Implements idempotent upsert pattern for data consistency.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-number">3. Analyze</div>
                    <strong>analyze_data.py</strong>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        Computes financial metrics (daily returns, rolling volatility), generates CSV reports, 
                        creates visualizations using matplotlib in headless mode.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="step">
                    <div class="step-number">4. Orchestrate</div>
                    <strong>run_all.py</strong>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        Executes complete workflow with progress tracking, error handling, and execution time reporting. 
                        Ensures reproducible end-to-end results.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Technical Implementation</h2>
            
            <h3>Database Schema Design</h3>
            <p>
                The <code>prices_daily</code> table uses a composite primary key on <code>(date, symbol)</code> to ensure 
                data integrity and prevent duplicates. Strategic indexing on <code>(symbol, date)</code> enables efficient 
                queries for time-series analysisâ€”critical for research workflows processing millions of rows.
            </p>
            
            <h3>Data Quality & Reproducibility</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Idempotent Operations:</strong> Pipeline can be re-run without creating duplicate data, ensuring consistent results</li>
                <li><strong>Version-Controlled Transformations:</strong> All data processing logic is tracked in Git for audit trails</li>
                <li><strong>Documented Data Lineage:</strong> Clear separation of Extract-Transform-Load stages for traceability</li>
                <li><strong>Error Handling:</strong> Graceful handling of API failures, missing data, and edge cases</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>CI/CD & Testing</h3>
            <p>
                GitHub Actions workflow tests the complete pipeline across Python 3.10, 3.11, and 3.12, validating:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Database creation and data integrity (row count validation)</li>
                <li>CSV report generation with content verification</li>
                <li>Chart creation and PNG format validation</li>
                <li>Cross-platform compatibility</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                This automated testing ensures reproducibilityâ€”any researcher or team member can clone the repository 
                and achieve identical results, a cornerstone of academic data workflows.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Pipeline Outputs</h2>
            <div class="outputs-grid">
                <div class="output-item">
                    <h4>Database</h4>
                    <p><code>db/marketdata.db</code></p>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        SQLite database with ~2,500 rows of daily price data, proper indexing, and composite primary keys 
                        for 10 major stocks over 365 days.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="output-item">
                    <h4>Summary Statistics</h4>
                    <p><code>reports/summary.csv</code></p>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        Per-symbol metrics: observation count, mean daily returns, standard deviation, and average trading volume.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="output-item">
                    <h4>Volatility Metrics</h4>
                    <p><code>reports/volatility.csv</code></p>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        20-day rolling volatility (annualized) for each symbol, computed using standard financial formulas.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="output-item">
                    <h4>Visualization</h4>
                    <p><code>reports/charts/adj_close_example.png</code></p>
                    <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 8px;">
                        Professional price chart demonstrating automated visualization capabilities for reporting and presentations.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

